prime minister toshiki kaifu has reprimanded for 
the unpardonable remark a cabinet minister who insulted us 
blacks according to a government official 
justice minister seiroku kajiyamas sept 21 comments touched 
off a series of angry protests at a news conference the 
64yearold political veteran compared foreign prostitutes in japan 
to black americans who ruin the atmosphere of neighborhoods 
they move into 
following a cabinet meeting last week kaifu called kajiyama 
into his office and told him his remarks were inappropriate and 
unpardonable giving him a stern warning foreign ministry 
spokesman taizo watanabe told a news briefing on tuesday 
the prime minister also wanted to make sure similar remarks 
would not be uttered by others watanabe said 
asked whether kajiyama would be forced to resign watanabe 
indicated the justice minister would retain his post because he 
later apologized for the comments and retracted them 
the comments were the latest by a japanese politician to provoke 
outrage from us minorities on friday angry demonstrators 
outside the japanese embassy in washington threatened a boycott 
against japanese products a group of about 30 foreigners also 
protested the remarks in a demonstration at the justice ministry in 
tokyo in tuesday kyodo news service reported 
