<DOCNO> AP901002-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the grayhaired woman stood 
motionless as the health workers fingers gently probed for the 
hard nodules under her skin that signal river blindness 
the ravages of years of infection are evident in the drooping 
skin of her face in her strangely elongated earlobes victoria 
morales is 49 she could pass for 69 
in her case the disease was curbed before the parasite spun a 
blinding web of microscopic filaments over her eyes 
it took years of painful treatment with a drug whose side 
effects made many afflicted peasants flee the rural health workers 
that prowl the rich coffee country of southern chiapas state 
mexico has been fighting river blindness for nearly a 
halfcentury suddenly it has a new weapon a gentler new drug 
called ivermectin 
rural health worker jose alfredo gordillo 32 recalls how he 
used to pressure people to take the old medication diethyl 
carbamazine used in mexico since 1953 
theyd say you have come to make us sick the sixyear 
veteran of the federal health departments river blindness brigades 
said 
some people simply refused the treatment was so unpleasant 
they paid the price with disfigurement premature aging or 
blindness 
but the side effects of ivermectin are milder and patients now 
readily come forward for treatment 
we have a problem gordillo said smiling the community 
leaders want everyone treated even if they arent sick 
ivermectin has raised hopes worldwide in the battle against a 
disease the world health organization says afflicts 18 million 
people in west africa latin america and parts of the middle east 
an estimated 300000 of them mostly in west africa have been 
blinded 
ivermectin was developed in the 1970s for livestock parasites 
when researchers discovered it was a safe effective treatment for 
onchocerciasis or river blindness the manufacturer merck and co 
of rahway nj decided to provide it for free 
a committee of medical experts based at the carter center in 
atlanta was set up to handle applications 
dr bruce dull the committees secretary said mexico which 
has one of the worlds oldest river blindness control programs 
began using ivermectin in may 1989 
the three varieties of black fly that carry river blindness in 
mexico are found in chiapas and nearby oaxaca only at the high 
cool altitudes that coffee grows best their larvae thrive in 
fastmoving streams 
coffee workers are those that are primarily affected and 
coffee is very important to our economy said dr andres martin 
a federal health official in mexico city 
he said 250000 people live in areas where river blindness is 
found about 20000 active cases have been diagnosed and 16000 
people are now taking ivermectin he said 
worldwide up to 500000 people take the drug which carries the 
brand name mectizan dull said 
twentyfive brigades of health workers spend up to 40 days at a 
time in the field hiking to remote villages sleeping on floors 
and treating the ailment peasants here call dogs skin or bad 
bruise piel de perro or mal morado because of the 
discoloration and disfigurement it causes 
there are 76 families on the ejido or communal farm of nuevo 
victoria in the heart of river blindness territory nearly all are 
affected by the disease said jorge velasco head of the regional 
river blindness program 
velasco dips his hand into a stream that runs through the ejido 
a squirming black goo covers his fingertip it is the larvae of the 
black flies that carry the disease 
the adult flies in turn inject the larvae of the parasite worm 
into humans with their bite the larvae grow into adult worms some 
as long as two feet which can live inside humans for 12 years and 
often cluster insie hard nodules under the skin 
but it is not the adults that do the damage its their 
offspring hundreds of millions of microworms called 
microfiliariae that swarm through human body tissue 
blindness is more common in africa than latin america but the 
microworms produce fierce itching and disfigurement in most 
victims 
they cause the skin to decay it becomes dark scaly flaccid 
and in the severest cases lesions develop over the eyes until 
sight is gone 
the effects are not reversible the only hope is to control the 
infection before the worst damage is done 
both drugs kill the microworms 
reactions to diethyl carbamazine swelling itching low blood 
pressure joint pain rash fever swollen lymph nodes can be so 
intense that it is not used in some rural areas where patients 
could not be hospitalized 
although ivermectin also produces swelling and itching the 
effects usually pass in days 
we give thanks to god that this was invented to help us 
said rumalda raymundo perez 51 who has taken both drugs 
neither drug is preventative or a complete cure but both kill 
the microworms and ivermectin appears to reduce the rate at which 
the adult worms breed 
although it appears annual treatment is effective mexico has 
permission to administer it twice a year to see if the rate of 
infection drops dull said 
the war against river blindness is a tropical disease success 
story in a country where thousands of children die each year of 
simple ailments like measles and diarrhea but hopes of eradication 
depend on elimination of the diseasebearing flies 
in my 23 years here nothing has been done to attack the 
vector carrier said vicente ardines martinez head of the 
transmittable disease program in chiapas a state famed for its 
lush forests mountains jungles and waterfalls 
but the environment is fragile we dont want to destroy it 
</TEXT>
