<TEXT>
republicans have won the iowa governors 
race in every election since 1968 but democrat don avenson is 
within striking range and thinks he can beat gov terry branstad to 
break the streak 
our time is coming says avenson the state house speaker 
we have a chance 
recent polls vary showing branstad with a lead ranging from a 
statistically insignificant three points to as much as 13 points 
avensons campaign is pursuing the following strategy 
raise onethird of the more than 3 million branstad will 
spend 
play off of iowas recent economic problems even though the 
state appears to have come through the worst 
reap some voter support from avensons prochoice position on 
abortion even though hes not counting on the issue to dominate 
the campaign and provide his margin of victory its not a silver 
bullet he says 
avenson hopes to chip away at the lead of a governor who is a 
tireless campaigner and who has never lost an election 
the last election i beat the majority leader and this time im 
going to beat the speaker of the house says the 43yearold 
branstad who also has been a state representative and lieutenant 
governor 
this governors been at it six days a week 14 or 16 hours a 
day for eight years says branstad i oftentimes have said 
the harder i work the luckier i get you kind of make your own 
luck 
while democrats have a lead of about 100000 in voter 
registration among the states 15 million registered voters 
branstad discounts that he argues there were more democrats than 
republicans when he won in 1982 and again in 1986 
branstad has called for restoring the death sentence a move 
polls show has broad support 
he feels the sentiments are changing among iowans and among 
legislators and this year the legislature may accept a limited 
death penalty said branstad spokesman richard vohs 
i think the governor is nervous i think hes saying this 
because hes politically nervous says avenson a veteran 
politician of 18 years in the state legislature eight as speaker 
in an era when many polls show voters leery of government 
avenson who is 46 takes an activist role 
we dont need more government we need more of the government 
we have he said i think we need to let government go unleash 
it and let it do its job we need to find ways to make government 
work again 
in the last 10 years weve grown older smaller and poorer 
he says if he were a football coach they would have fired him a 
long time ago for that kind of a record 
that approach may not be effective with the states economy 
stronger than during the depths of a farmbased recession 
throughout the 1980s 
our goal in the 90s is to continue the economic comeback that 
we began in the past few years says branstad 
