by avenson and opposed by branstad 
with polls showing that twothirds of iowans consider themselves 
prochoice avenson hoped that would translate into votes he 
conceded that his private polling shows prochoice voters still 
split between the two candidates and not familiar with their 
positions 
while branstad takes an antiabortion position he hasnt asked 
the legislature to impose restrictions and he picked a prochoice 
woman state sen joy corning as his running mate 
i dont want to tear this state apart over an emotional 
issue branstad argues 
you see the antichoice vote all of them support terry 
branstad said avenson but the prochoice vote hasnt come all 
the way over because i havent made it clear 
we will cause that movement to take place because we will make 
it very clear said avenson 
other activists argue the issue will help prochoice candidates 
but only around the fringes 
iowa democratic chairman john roehrick said movement will come 
as independent voters focus in the final weeks 
weve still got five weeks to go until the election said 
roehrick i dont think it will be the only issue i think it 
means two to four points 
