<TEXT>
president bush wants to keep us aid flowing 
to pakistan even though there is evidence the country is violating 
rules against nuclear weapons proliferation administration and 
congressional sources say 
senior state department officials are working on capitol hill to 
lift the legal requirement that bars pakistan the third largest 
recipient of us aid from getting any money if it presses ahead 
with nuclear bomb development 
us aid to pakistan technically came to a halt monday the 
beginning of the 1991 fiscal year because bush had not issued the 
required annual certification that pakistan does not possess a 
nuclear bomb and that continued us aid will reduce the prospect 
for development of atomic weapons 
pakistan has scheduled national elections for oct 24 to replace 
the government of former prime minister benazir bhutto who was 
removed from office two months ago amid charges of corruption 
the administration wants to give the new government that emerges 
after those elections time to curb or roll back the countrys 
nuclear weapons program before making a decision on cutting off 
aid said sources who spoke on condition of anonymity 
senior administration officials including undersecretary of 
state reginald bartholomew and deputy assistant secretary teresita 
schaffer went to capitol hill last week to ask for a waiver the 
idea was received coolly among key house officials including rep 
david obey dwis chairman of the foreign aid appropriations 
subcommittee and rep stephen solarz dny chairman of the 
subcommittee on asia 
the administration which typically finds a warmer welcome in 
the senate is hoping it can pursue the waiver there either as an 
amendment to the foreign aid bill that comes up for committee 
consideration today or on another bill before congress adjourns 
later this month 
leonard spector a weapons proliferation analyst at the carnegie 
endowment for international peace said policymakers appear afraid 
to assert us values adopting a waiver he said would mean we 
are in effect announcing to the world that pakistan has nuclear 
weapons and we just dont care 
but an administration official said it is prudent to withhold 
judgment on the certification until after we get beyond this 
point of flux and set up a dialogue with the new government 
while the white house would like to see a yearlong waiver it will 
settle for six months the official said 
nobodys jumping up and down about it but they are 
sympathetic and they understand the seriousness of the issue the 
official added 
pakistan has provided the base for covert us aid to afghan 
rebels in the 1980s and also has promised troops to help defend 
saudi arabia from iraq 
bhutto who was warmly received when she promised her country 
would not develop a nuclear bomb during a 1989 speech to congress 
was removed from power on aug 6 while she is among those vying 
for control in the new elections analysts say she is unlikely to 
regain power 
uspakistani relations have benn shaky since bhuttos ouster 
a minister in the caretaker cabinet urged that us ambassador 
robert oakley be recalled for questioning the impartiality of 
tribunals looking into government corruption and pakistan lodged 
an official protest of his remarks 
sources on capitol hill and others with access to top pakistani 
officials said there are fears that pakistan has produced enriched 
uranium in a form that could be the basis for a bomb stepping over 
the line that both sides understood would trigger an aid cutoff 
at the state department spokesman richard boucher said only 
that the question of whether to issue the presidential 
certification is still under review and that aid cannot be 
provided until a certification is issued 
pakistan received nearly 580 million in us military and 
economic aid in fiscal 1990 making it the third largest recipient 
