<TEXT>
the deregulatory policies of the reagan 
administration helped contain the savings and loan crisis former 
treasury secretary donald t regan is telling skeptical 
congressional democrats 
i think the thrift industry would have gone into the tank 
sooner and may have never emerged regan told the house banking 
committee at the first in a series of hearings on the causes of the 
sampl mess 
regan who was treasury secretary from 1981 to 1985 said that 
after interest rates soared in the early 1980s it became clear that 
a financial business confined to taking deposits from savers and 
lending the money to home buyers could not survive 
he said he had favored giving thrifts the same investment powers 
as commercial banks but had opposed the broader deregulation in 
some states that had given thrifts nonbank powers 
the committee also heard on monday from richard t pratt who 
served as the nations top thrift regulator from 1981 to 1982 
pratt defended his decision to allow sampls to hide their losses with 
accounting techniques 
pratt said when he took office nearly every sampl in the country 
was technically insolvent because soaring interest rates had 
drastically cut the value of their lowinterest fixedrate 
mortgages 
regulators strategy was to close the worst institutions and to 
buy time for the others until interest rates fell as they did he 
said 
panel members pressed regan who was chairman of merrill lynch 
before becoming treasury secretary on his involvement with the 
development of socalled brokered deposits 
such highinterest deposits placed by wall street brokerage 
houses usually in amounts just under the 100000 deposit 
insurance limit are blamed for fueling the explosive growth in 
risky investments at many sampls 
regan however said he had disqualified himself from any policy 
matters affecting brokered deposits because of his connection to 
merrill lynch he said the firm did not deal in them extensively 
until after he left 
i want a blood test as far as being the father of brokered 
deposits i am not in no way shape or fashion he said 
rep joseph kennedy dmass countered that regan allowed his 
subordinate deputy treasury secretary rt mcnamar to forcefully 
advocate their use 
edwin gray the nations top thrift regulator from 1983 to 1987 
has accused regan of trying to force him from office when he tried 
to rein in the industry in general and brokered deposits in 
particular 
regan who previously had not had a chance to reply to gray in a 
public forum described him as an absentee lax regulator 
in 1985 when i became white house chief of staff i began 
to hear rumors that this man was not paying attention he was part 
of the problem not the solution he was sort of a front for 
the industry i didnt like that regan said 
he said that between september 1983 and june 1986 gray was in 
his office only 397 weekdays and absent 466 days he also noted 
that gray was forced to repay his agency the federal home loan 
bank board 26000 for travel and entertainment 
he want to pebble beach he went to greenbriar my crack was 
i think hes working more on his golf handicap than hes working 
on the thrifts regan said 
gray and former federal reserve board chairman paul volcker are 
scheduled to appear before the committee wednesday the committee 
chairman rep henry b gonzalez dtexas plans to hear from 
carter administration officials later 
in other sampl developments monday 
federal regulators said they had transferred most offices of 
the phoenixbased merabank to bank of america estimating the 
bailout of the thrift once arizonas largest at 1 billion 
bank of america arizona a subsidiary of the san franciscobased 
holding company is taking over merabanks 66 arizona branches the 
resolution trust corp said the agency will keep merabanks seven 
texas branches for later sale 
texas and california savings and loans dominate a list of the 
top 100 federal thrift investigations by the justice department 
national mortgage news a weekly trade newspaper reported 
there were 36 texas sampls on the list which has not been 
publicly released and 20 from california oklahoma and illinois 
and eight institutions listed florida had six colorado five and 
louisiana and new jersey four each 
