<TEXT>
the senate ethics committee is summoning five 
senators to explain their assistance for charles h keating jr at 
a time his lincoln savings and loan was plummeting toward a massive 
collapse 
the senators will appear over the next two weeks the committee 
announced monday after which the panel will act on recommendations 
from its special counsel 
congressional sources said counsel robert s bennett has 
recommended that the investigation go forward for democratic sens 
alan cranston of california donald w riegle jr of michigan and 
dennis deconcini of arizona 
bennett also recommended that the investigations of sens john 
mccain rariz and john glenn dohio be dismissed the sources 
said 
continuation of any of the cases could mean triallike hearings 
would be scheduled probably next year 
the sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said bennetts 
report establishes crucial links between the timing of 
contributions by keating to cranston riegle and deconcini and 
actions they took on keatings behalf 
the conclusion was there was no connection between the 
contributions and actions of glenn and mccain one source said 
the links were instrumental in bennetts recommendations said 
another source who added bennetts conclusions are not based on a 
single factor but o a pattern and practice of behavior by each 
senator 
glenn and mccain are scheduled to appear before the sixmember 
ethics panel this week sources said it was not known when the 
other senators will testify 
under our existing practices the committee must give each 
senator under investigation the opportunity to be heard by the 
committee in executive session before any decisions are made a 
committee statement said following these meetings with the 
senators the committee will meet to decide how it will proceed 
the five senators received a total of 13 million from keating 
and his associates for their campaigns and causes and intervened 
with us banking regulators on behalf of the former head of 
lincoln savings and loan of irvine calif 
the federal government seized keatings thrift in april 1989 it 
could cost taxpayers more than 2 billion to cover the losses from 
the collapse 
the senators have said they intervened with regulators 
especially in two key meetings in april 1987 because keating made 
a persuasive case that his sampl was being treated unfairly all have 
denied that their intervention was driven by the donations 
public documents and statements show some links between the 
contributions and contacts with regulators by riegle cranston and 
deconcini 
however bennett reportedly has much more precise connections 
involving the timing 
the public record shows that 
keating was the host of a fundraiser for riegle in detroit on 
march 23 1987 less than two weeks before four senators met with 
the nations chief thrift regulator april 2 1987 riegle said he 
received 78250 from keating and his associates at the 
fundraiser 
riegle didnt attend that april 2 meeting although he suggested 
it be held he was at an april 9 meeting between all five senators 
and regulators examining lincoln 
cranston solicited 850000 from keating for three voter 
registration projects the contributions began in june 1987 two 
months after the meetings with regulators and continued through 
february 1988 cranston also received 39000 from keating and his 
associates for his 1986 reelection campaign 
deconcini received 15000 in campaign donations from keating 
or his associates in 1986 before the meetings with regulators and 
an additional 5000 in october 1987 
in addition to the april 1987 meetings deconcini and cranston 
continued a series of contacts with regulators right up to the time 
the thrift was seized in april 1989 both said they intervened in 
an effort to get lincoln sold rather than seized by the 
government in order to save jobs 
the links between those contacts and contributions could not 
immediately be determined 
at the april 2 1987 meeting cranston mccain deconcini and 
glenn discussed lincoln with edwin j gray then chairman of the 
federal home loan bank board 
gray told the house banking committee last november that riegle 
suggested the meeting with senators riegle acknowledged that such 
a meeting was one of the issues he discussed with gray a month 
earlier but he denied actually arranging the session 
gray testified that the four senators at the april 2 meeting 
offered a deal on keatings behalf if regulators waived a rule 
prohibiting risky investments for lincoln the thrift would finance 
more home mortgages all four senators vigorously denied that a 
deal was offered 
on april 9 1987 all five senators meeting with the san 
franciscobased regulators who were examining lincoln were told 
that allegations against keatings thrift were so serious that 
criminal referrals were being made to the justice department 
