<TEXT>
new television sets with 13inch screens or 
larger would have to include builtin decoders for displaying 
closed captions for the deaf under legislation awaiting president 
bushs signature 
the house gave final approval to the bill monday by voice vote 
the senate passed it in july 
the measure requires tv sets sold after july 1993 to be equipped 
with circuitry for converting audio portions of a tv program into 
subtitles on the screen decoders are available now but they sell 
for 160 to 200 separately 
the house energy and commerce committee estimated that including 
the chips at manufacture would add no more than 15 to the retail 
price 
in addition to the estimated 20 million to 24 million americans 
who are deaf or hearing impaired backers said the decoders also 
would benefit millions of children and functionally illiterate 
adults in learning to read as wells as immigrants trying to learn 
english 
all primetime television shows broadcast by the three major 
networks now carry closed captions as do most national news shows 
and sports events 
 
 
