farewell to the vessel monday during the ceremony at the submarine 
base on point loma 
we are here to close with honor the active life of the 
blueback said a chokedup cmdr thomas a grassi its time to 
say farewell to an era and to a gallant lady 
the blueback which was commissioned in 1959 never saw battle 
and most of the time it patrolled the pacific but it did its part 
for posterity 
it made the first underwater voyage from japan to san diego in 
23 days in 1989 the blueback was used as a soviet submarine in 
the film the hunt for red october 
its final trip will be to the navys submarine graveyard in 
bremerton wash 
grassi was the last of 15 blueback skippers the 215foot 
submarine is a floating hunk of cold black metal he said 
it has been her crew which made her alive 
taps sounded as the crew lowered the vessels commissioning 
pennant the banner was given to grassi who is retiring along with 
the sub 
the ceremony ended an era that began in 1912 when the navy 
launched its first dieselpowered submarine the skipjack the 
navys only diesel submarine still in service the dolphin is a 
noncombatant research ship 
the transition to a nuclear sub fleet began in 1954 with the 
nautilus 
defenders of diesel submarines contend they are quieter harder 
for an enemy to find and cheaper than their nuclearpowered 
counterparts 
navy officials argue that the newer nuclear models are faster 
and more efficient 
nuclear submarines offer the ability and the endurance to 
deploy on station for many days as opposed to the diesel which is 
less capable in a forwarddeployed role said navy spokesman lt 
greg smith 
diesel engines drove the blueback on the surface and 
highcapacity storage batteries powered electric motors when it was 
submerged 
