<TEXT>
american companies surveyed before the persian 
gulf crisis said they planned to boost their overseas spending by 1 
percent in 1991 the government said tuesday 
the commerce department said a survey conducted in june showed 
that majorityowned foreign affiliates of us companies planned 
566 billion in capital spending next year up from 56 billion in 
planned expenditures in 1990 
but the department said the 1991 plans should be viewed with 
particular caution because the most recent survey was conducted 
before the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait 
developments in the middle east following the invasion may 
influence worldwide economic conditions investment opportunities 
and oil prices which may significantly change firms capital 
spending plans it said 
the 17 percent increase in 1990 spending plans was up from a 13 
percent planned increase reported in a survey last december actual 
capital expenditures in 1989 totaled 479 billion 
the level of capital expenditures indicates that us parent 
companies plan to maintain their recent emphasis on overseas 
operations the report said 
the largest increases were planned in germany up 18 percent to 
63 billion and japan up 15 percent to 26 billion 
even before the energy disruption of the persian gulf crisis 
the report said petroleum affiliates planned to increase spending 
by 2 percent to 159 billion in 1991 the increases include oil 
tanker construction and oil and gas extraction in canada norway 
nigeria and southeast asia 
petroleum firms attracted by host government incentives and 
potentially larger exploitable oil and gas reserves than those in 
the united states have been increasing their overseas spending 
relative to their domestic spending for exploration and 
development it added 
at the same time it said completed projects will result in 
spending declines in australia britain and the caribbean 
manufacturing affiliates plan to increase spending by 1 percent 
to 282 billion increases are planned in nonelectrical 
machinery transportation equipment and chemicals 
manufacturers have been attracted by several favorable 
conditions abroad increasing economic integration in the european 
communities movement toward marketoriented economic systems in 
eastern europe an improved investment climate in latin america and 
rapid economic growth in east asia it continued 
large investments in the european communities account for the 
bulk of the planned increase in spending on nonelectrical 
machinery mainly computers and transportation equipment 
computer manufacturing affiliates in the european communities 
plan to build facilities to produce a new generation of highspeed 
semiconductors and to meet rising demand for personal computers 
the department said 
automotive manufacturing affiliates in the european 
communities are planning extensive projects to reduce production 
costs and introduce product improvements in response to rising 
competition from japaneseowned firms and growing consumer 
demand it added 
in chemicals sizable investments are planned in japan where 
an affiliate is building a product development center it said 
spending declines related to project completions are planned 
in primary and fabricated metals other manufacturing mainly 
rubber and paper products electrical machinery and food products 
the report said 
