<TEXT>
two activist groups asked the government 
tuesday to tighten regulations to make sure negative political ads 
clearly identify the candidate making the attack 
people for the american way and the media access project said 
many attack ads fail to adequately identify their sponsors in a 
concerted attempt to confuse and deceive voters 
the american public by and large does not like negative 
television commercials said art kropp president of people for 
the american way on the other hand they are effective if 
there is no connection made to the candidate who is paying for 
them 
candidates pictures should appear for at least four seconds and 
cover at least 20 percent of the tv screen the two groups said in 
a petition to the federal communications commission 
they also said text identifying the sponsor should appear for at 
least four seconds and measure at least 4 percent of the vertical 
height of the tv screen 
currently special discounted advertising rates are available to 
candidates whose commercials contain identifications that are 
readily legible and on screen long enough to be read by the average 
viewer 
but the two groups that filed the fcc complaint showed a tape of 
political commercials they say show that broadcasters are not 
meeting those standards 
the ads including some from hot governors races in california 
and texas feature tiny pictures and text identifying the source of 
the ads sometimes the sponsorship information appears for only a 
second or two often it appears against a backdrop of newspaper 
clips or alongside distractions such as a moving dog or moving 
text 
andrew jay schwartzman an attorney with the media access 
project said the current vague standards make broadcasters 
reluctant to reject ads as soon as one broadcaster in a 
community accepts a given ad the pressure becomes 
insurmountable he said 
both groups stressed that they are not promoting censorship or 
regulation of ad content negative ads will be a part of 
campaigns forever what were aiming for is basically truth in 
advertising kropp said 
he and schwartzman said the abuse is bipartisan and occurs at 
all levels with some of the worst cases occurring in local or 
primary races involving inexperienced and unknown candidates 
they said the problems arise mainly in negative spots because 
they work best with voters when the sponsoring candidate is not 
associated with the attack 
in positive commercials on the other hand the candidates 
happily appear standing in their air force uniform bouncing 
children on their knee or holding the hand of a senior citizen 
schwartzman said 
the two said they do not expect the fcc to decide on their 
petition before next months election but they want the agency to 
issue an interim notice reminding broadcasters of their 
responsibilities under current rules 
milton gross chief of the fccs political branch said the last 
such notice was issued in september 1977 he said the agency 
advises individual broadcasters of their obligations when specific 
complaints arise but has never received a broad complaint like the 
one filed tuesday 
people for the american way describes itself as a nonpartisan 
constitutional liberties group with 290000 members the media 
access project is a public interest telecommunications law firm 
</TEXT>
