<TEXT>
lithuania and the soviet union agreed tuesday to 
conduct their economic and trade relations for 1991 as equal 
partners in a further stride toward independence for the baltic 
republic 
the first step has been taken and it was a major step and we 
did not lose our bearings lithuanian president vytautas 
landsbergis told a news conference after the kremlin meeting 
the talks headed on the soviet side by prime minister nikolai 
ryzhkov were the first at such a high level since lithuania 
suspended its march 11 declaration of independence following the 
kremlins economic embargo against the republic 
a communique issued afterward also mentioned preparations for 
future negotiations that is a significant concession by the 
soviet side because president mikhail s gorbachev has maintained 
bilateral negotiations can occur only between two nations and 
not between the kremlin and a republic 
asked whether the kremlin has changed its view on independence 
for lithuania and is now willing to negotiate landsbergis replied 
wed like to think it is so yet further meetings will show if it 
really is so 
on the lithuanian side the communique said the republic will 
discuss addressing the opinions of various groups of residents 
a reference to the interests of the large russian population of 
the baltic republic who oppose independence the kremlin has 
alleged that lithuanias russian population has been the object of 
discrimination during the republics independence drive 
according to the communique the delegations agreed that their 
further activities will be conducted according to bilateral trade 
and economic relations for the year 1991 
lithuanian prime minister kazimiera prunskiene explained the 
agreement would mean closer economic cooperation with the 
soviet union based on more of a partnership principle rather than 
the previous practice of a republics rigid subordination to the 
central government 
the content of lithuanias trade agreements with the soviet 
union will depend on what functions the other republics delegate to 
the central government she said 
this does not mean that the lithuanian republic will delegate 
any functions of the governing of its economy to the soviet 
union she said and it does not mean that lithuania is going 
to sign the union treaty or be a part of the soviet economy 
the union treaty which is still being negotiated will define 
the relationship between the kremlin and the republics gorbachev 
has proposed a loose confederation with strong economic links but 
republics such as the baltics who are seeking independence say it 
does not go far enough 
the agreement reached tuesday would not affect any other 
bilateral pacts lithuania has struck with any of the other 14 
soviet republics she said 
mrs prunskiene said experts would soon begin work on 
lithuanias economic cooperation with the soviet union in 1991 in 
matters of foreign economic trade customs and tariffs and other 
issues 
landsbergis who led the republics delegation said that 
although the fourhour kremlin meeting was 100 times better than 
could be reflected in the communique he did not foresee rapid 
political independence 
probably well have to cover a long path of other such 
meetings before we can commence official negotiations and sign an 
appropriate protocol landsbergis said 
the agreement might not meet with universal approval in 
lithuania where sentiment is strong for complete independence one 
western diplomatic expert said 
moscow hopes it if it gets an agreement without territorial 
concessions it will be to its advantage said the diplomat 
speaking on condition he not be further identified 
but mrs prunskiene and landsbergis feel the negotiations 
convey legitimacy to the republics independence declaration of 
march 11 he said 
when mrs prunskiene and landsbergis report back to the 
proindependence lithuanian parliament they can expect reaction 
divided into three camps he said 
the most sympathetic group of lithuanian lawmakers believes in 
a stepbystep process and that an agreement for bilateral 
economic cooperation is useful and lends momentum for further 
negotiations 
the middle camp believes in the necessity for a political 
agreement but is generally sympathetic to the economic talks 
the third group the most radical says dont negotiate at 
all the soviet union is falling apart and all we have to do is 
wait 
lithuania and the soviet union agreed to set up a working group 
headed by soviet deputy prime minister vitaly doguzhiyev and 
lithuanian deputy prime minister romualdas ozolas who will draft 
proposals in two weeks to prepare for official negotiations the 
communique said 
the soviet union also agreed to increase pension payments to 
world war ii veterans in lithuania as of oct 1 he said 
commenting on the reunification of germany and its meaning for 
the baltic republics which were annexed by the soviet union 
following a secret pact between josef stalin and adolf hitler 
landsbergis said we hope that our independence also the 
independence of latvia and estonia would be the last steps of the 
second world war 
