<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency fails to 
monitor the effectiveness of disinfectants and up to 20 percent of 
the products sold to kill diseasecausing germs may not work a 
government study says 
in a report released to congress on tuesday the general 
accounting office said the epa has not inspected the majority of 
laboratories that test disinfectants and that the agency lacks 
assurance methods to prove the germkillers are valid 
epas policy of let the buyer beware for disinfectants may 
be compromising public health and wasting consumer dollars the 
gaos richard l hembra said in a statement released with the 
report 
the gao report said estimates by the epas own experts are that 
an estimated 20 percent of all disinfectants fail to kill germs or 
viruses as they are supposed to and that tests in some states show 
that more than 40 percent of the compounds are ineffective 
americans spend about 1 billion a year on disinfectants to kill 
diseasekilling germs sterilize food preparation areas surgical 
tools and bathrooms and prevent infectious disease there are about 
4100 such products registered by the government 
the epa is directed by law to register disinfectants and to 
assure that they are effective but the gao said the agency depends 
on test data submitted by manufacturers and that the epa lacks 
assurance that the test methods and performance standards used 
are valid 
the report said it found the epa had inspected only a small 
percentage of the labs that test disinfectants and in factwas 
aware of only 12 of the 92 labs that had performed these studies 
after labs have been inspected the study said it takes the epa 
from five months to more than 2 years to process the reports 
even the methods of conducting disinfectant tests the report 
said are uncertain 
almost all of the eparecommended efficacy test methods and 
performance standards have been embroiled in scientific controversy 
for over a decade the report said the agency has done little to 
resolve these uncertainties and it inadequately managed a 
384000 study of the issue at the university of north carolina 
anne lindsay te epa official who supervises the disinfectant 
registration said her agency has monitored labs that do about 40 
percent of the testing she also said the agency is developing a 
reenforcement strategy to assure that manufacturers accurately 
report test data 
the gao report said that from 1977 to 1982 the epas own lab 
found that 42 percent of all disinfectant samples failed efficacy 
tests in 1982 the agency closed its lab and since then the epa has 
depended on industry selftesting lindsay said only one 
manufacturer has reported a batch of disinfectant that failed to 
pass the tests 
she said the epa generally agreed with the issues raised in 
the gao report and is attempting to improve the system 
