<TEXT>
amputees who wear artificial feet can sense 
the floor with a new electronic device that was developed by a 
company here and made its national debut tuesday 
the sabolich senseoffeel system was developed by john 
sabolich president of the sabolich prosthetic amp research center 
it was demonstrated on the abctv program good morning 
america 
the system uses small pressure transducers implanted in the 
artificial foot to signal electrodes in the socket of the 
prosthesis the electrodes in turn stimulate the skin of the limb 
stump and transmit sensation to the brain 
the 1400 electronic system is powered by a standard 9volt 
battery and can be used by any lowerlimb amputee sabolich said 
its the most incredible thing said holly howard an 
abovetheknee amputee from tyler texas who is one of 20 people 
testing the device so far for the first time in 10 years i can 
feel my foot and know where it is 
sabolich said the invention he first conceived of eight years 
ago might also have the potential to reduce and even eliminate 
socalled phantom pain for amputees who feel discomfort as if from 
the missing limb 
the brain really likes to have information from the floor 
sabolich said when it doesnt have information from the floor 
the nerves sort of dangle and that increases phantom pain and 
doesnt let the person know where their foot is on the ground 
dr william n harsha an oklahoma city orthopedic surgeon 
asked to comment on the system said he had not known of it 
except in the research stage and john sabolich has been in the 
forefront of that 
i would think it would be of great benefit harsha said 
it would enable the patient to know where his foot iswhen he is 
walking going up and down the stairs each of these movements is 
different and requires different control 
</TEXT>
