<TEXT>
us air force veterans involved in the spraying 
of agent orange and other herbicides during the vietnam war are as 
healthy as those not exposed to the chemicals air force 
researchers reported 
two studies reported in the oct 10th edition of the journal of 
the american medical association compared the mortality rates and 
physical health of veterans of operation ranch hand the unit 
responsible for the sprayings and air force veterans who served 
concurrently in other units 
an evaluation of cumulative and allcausing mortality revealed 
no statistically significant differences between ranch hands and 
comparison subjects said air force col william h wolfe 
coauthor of the studies 
the first study found a significant increase in digestive system 
disease deaths among the veterans but most were linked to 
alcoholism not to herbicidal exposure 
a second study comparing the physical health of 995 ranch hand 
veterans to 1299 other veterans found that the two groups 
reported similar health problems the study was based on physical 
exams administered in 1982 1985 and 1987 
the researchers reported that the few associations found between 
physical health and exposure to the herbicides were weak and 
inconsistent 
we are left with the interpretation that the few positive 
findings are not supportive of a hypothesis of adverse health 
effects in ranch hands the authors wrote in the journal 
