<TEXT>
the budget deal reached by the budget summiteers 
comes with the claim of 500 billion in savings over the next five 
years but that claim doesnt mean overall cuts in government 
spending 
government spending will continue to grow by 55 billion in 
fiscal 1991 a 45 percent rise and by 222 billion in the next 
five years an increase of 184 percent it will be financed mainly 
by taxing rather than cutting 
confusion over this aspect of the agreement between the white 
house and congressional leaders afflicts not just the public but 
tax and finance experts and members of congress some of whom might 
have been directly involved 
in many instances the cuts referred to are reductions in 
planned or proposed spending rather than actual spending medicare 
spending for instance will be cut by 46 billion but grow by 
44 billion in fiscal 1991 
on a more personal basis the monthly tax that senior citizens 
pay to medicare will be increased but the revenues so generated 
are counted in the agreement as a spending cut 
in a scorching criticism of the agreement scott hodge and 
daniel mitchell of the heritage foundation who supplied these 
figures claim negotiatiors sought to blunt negative reaction by 
conspiring to cook the books 
that term is sometimes used by companies to hide financial 
shenanigans from auditors and shareholders or to paint a 
rosierthanreal picture hodge and mitchell suggest that this 
seems to have been a goal of the negotiators too 
they contend that the agreement is the most successful use of 
blue smoke and mirrors to date by the budget summiteers and that 
few senators and congressmen can figure out what it is they are 
asked to vote on 
they conclude that in spite of the blue smoke the glare and the 
shadows it is quite clear that congress cannot control its 
spending and that by means of higher taxes it seeks to shift the 
burden from itself to the taxpayer 
the affect they say might be enough to push the country into a 
fullblown recession but that isnt the way the summitteers see 
it instead of slowing the economy they assume it will spur it to 
much greater growth 
should that growth double this years growth rate in 1991 and 
almost triple that rate in 1992 fail to develop so also will 
some of the alleged savings but at least two other dangers must be 
considered too 
1 congress could begin almost immediately to offset any true 
cuts with new spending measures the danger is real massive tax 
cuts early in the 1980s were entirely offset by massive spending 
well before the end of the decade 
2 the agreement assumes that the federal reserve board will be 
so impressed by the negotiators efforts that it will adopt an 
easier money policy which would mean lower interest rates 
but hodge and mitchell argue the agreement could worsen rather 
than lessen inflation if inflation worsens interest rates arent 
likely to fall and they say 25 billion of the alleged savings 
assume lower rates 
these are the ingredients of a spirited discussion for congress 
during which some of the hazier aspects might become clearer and 
any dangers to the economy be reexamined without the blinding 
glare of mirrors 
potentially the political damage could be worse the 
foundation a conservative think tank has strongly supported 
presidents reagan and bush and has had much intellectual input and 
influence in their administrations 
while hodge and mitchell might not speak for the entire 
foundation their views were distributed by it and so far as is 
known they remain in good standing 
</TEXT>
