the house has sent legislation to president 
bush that would reinstate limits on commercial advertising on 
childrens television shows 
the bush administration opposes the legislation saying it would 
create new and extremely serious first amendment problems 
involving free speech 
the bill was approved on voice vote monday in the house without 
dissent it also has been approved by the senate 
the legislation would limit commercial advertising during 
childrens programming to 10 minutes an hour on weekends and 12 
minutes an hour on weekdays 
rep edward j markey dmass said too many stations now allow 
for 13 minutes to 17 minutes of advertising during each hour of 
childrens programming 
the bill also would require the federal communications 
commission in renewing the licenses of television stations to 
weigh how well broadcasters are serving the educational and 
informational needs of children 
and it would establish a federally funded national endowment for 
childrens educational television to subsidize the production of 
childrens programming the endowment would be funded at 2 million 
in 1991 and 4 million the next year 
the legislation would effectively reverse the reagan 
administrations deregulation of the commercial content of 
childrens tv programming in 1984 
