<TEXT>
farmers should prepare themselves for lower 
target prices as congress looks for ways to cut the agriculture 
budget by 13 billion over the next five years farm organization 
officials say 
government officials said monday that the cuts would be painful 
although no one could give details yet on how the cut agreed to by 
white house and congressional negotiators to reduce the deficit 
would be accomplished 
we want the target prices to stay at the current levels but 
it would be difficult if not impossible to make the magnitude of 
cuts they have to make without doing something on the target 
prices said don lipton media relations director for the 
american farm bureau federation 
they said they were going to freeze target prices but 
theres no way with this budget agreement that can happen said 
david senter national director of american agriculture movement 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas who helped negotiate the agreement 
said agriculture has taken a tough hit 
any cut in usdas budget is painful for our farmers and 
ranchers said agriculture secretary clayton yeutter however 
we have no oter alternative as a country but to reduce our federal 
budget deficit 
senate agriculture committee chairman patrick leahy dvt 
said we will all have to make deep and painful cuts in many 
important programs to pay for a deficit caused by the sampl scandal 
and the freewheeling economic policies and tax giveaways of the 
1980s 
unfortunately the people who had the party arent the ones 
paying the tab said leahy 
yeutter said farmers would be willing to take their share of the 
cuts as long as they are fair 
in the short run these budget reductions coupled with rising 
fuel costs will squeeze agriculture hard he said we will have 
to tighten our belts and that is not easily done but in the long 
run we will all be better off if we can restore fiscal sanity to 
this nation 
the cuts will be as fair as possible said leahy who also 
chairs the housesenate conference committee working on the 1990 
farm bill 
the farm bills approved by the house and senate call for 54 
billion in spending on commodities subsidies over the next five 
years 
under the budget agreement that figure must be cut 25 percent 
with about 13 billion coming out of the budget for the 1991 
fiscal year which began monday 
the problem this year is that all but about 292 billion of the 
amount budgeted for fiscal 1991 is payment on expenses carried over 
from 1990 that cannot be eliminated 
that means it might be back to the drawing board on commodity 
support programs in the farm bill said several aides close to the 
process 
we dont want to see target prices dropped but wed rather 
see target prices go down than loan rates go up said lipton of 
the farm bureau 
loan rates are the amount farmers can borrow from the government 
by using their crops as collateral thus the loans are a support 
or a guaranteed floor price for the commodities 
farmers have the option of forfeiting their crops collateral 
and canceling the debt if market prices are low or paying off the 
loan and selling or using the commodities when market prices 
improve 
the administration and others favoring marketoriented programs 
say high loan rates result in government ownership of surplus 
commodities that should be moving into export at world prices 
lipton said the agriculture industry as a whole wont suffer 
extremely if cuts are made its not as dependent on government 
programs as it was in the mid80s he said 
lipton said many farmers no longer participate in government 
programs either because their farms are so big they can sustain 
themselves even when market prices are low or because they are 
smaller speciality operations 
however leland swenson president of national farmers union 
said the 13 billion slash in usda programs would throw the farm 
sector into a tailspin 
farmers are facing disastrous grain prices higher input costs 
as the result of oil prices and now 13 billion in cuts that will 
come directly out of farm income under the 1990 farm bill 
structure swenson said 
youve got some new variables to work with now the mideast 
situation falling wheat prices and now budget cuts have all come 
to roost since the farm bill passed the two houses he said 
