<TEXT>
a manufacturer of the armys main tactical 
field radio was ordered tuesday to pay 38 million for conspiring 
to defraud the government on defense contracts by falsifying 
reliability test results 
esystems inc of dallas received the sentence from us 
district judge william terrell hodges after formally pleading 
guilty to a threecount criminal information 
prosecutors charged the company repeatedly altered performance 
records and concealed repairs and defects in tests of the field 
radios to ensure the army would accept and pay for them 
the investigation began in 1985 after the army ended two 
esystems contracts to build radios at its memcor division in 
bushnell the company had been building the armys principal 
vehiclecarried field radios since 1969 
esystems appealed the termination and the testing program 
irregularities were noticed at that time the company later sued 
the government over the termination 
in its plea esystems agreed to pay a 2 million criminal fine 
and 18 million in restitution the company also is to drop its 
pending 38 million lawsuit against the government 
in addition the company will pay 850000 to cover any 
potential civil claims the government may bring 
in august three former managers and a former supervisor at 
memcor were indicted on charges of repeatedly falsifying records 
and test results to conceal failures and defects in the radios 
in january a frontline production supervisor sadonna s 
hobbs was convicted of perjury relating to her denials of this 
activity she is serving a 16month prison sentence 
