<TEXT>
a government support package helped propel tokyo 
stocks to their biggest oneday jump in history tuesday but left 
uncertain prospects for an extended rebound from the worst market 
decline in more than 30 years 
the closely watched nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues 
leaped 267655 points or 1324 percent to 2289841 after the 
ministry of finance announced emergency measures to shore up the 
ailing market 
the market receded slightly in early trading wednesday on profit 
taking before resuming its climb as the nikkei posted a 
33116point gain in the morning session 
as the largest singleday gain ever tuesdays market eclipsed 
the 929 percent rebound posted a day after the stock market 
crashed three years ago when the nikkei rose 203732 points to 
2394740 
the support from the finance ministry boosted the markets 
sentiment i believe institutional investors as well as individual 
buyers now cant resist investing at the current low levels said 
toshiyuki nishiguchi a trader with daiwa securities 
the unprecedented jump came after a ninemonth meltdown that had 
erased nearly half the markets value the equivalent of 21 
trillion since the end of last year the protracted slide was the 
worst since the korean war in the early 1950s market observers 
said 
the foreign ministrys measures themselves were minor 
adjustments but because they sent a message of support to the 
markets their psychological impact was considerable 
the measures were aimed at spurring buying and reducing market 
volatility they included easing restrictions on the purchase of 
stock on credit and shortening the hours for futures and options 
trading 
on monday before finance minister ryutaro hashimoto signaled 
the governments intentions market watchers had been predicting 
the nikkei would plummet below the 15000 mark after the market 
began to rally some were calling for a return to 23000 or even 
25000 
this just shows how very fragile investor sentiment is said 
amy yip manager of equity sales at baring securities ltd 
the nikkeis comeback began late in monday trading on comments 
from hashimoto indicating that the government was about to act to 
stem the markets slide the nikkei which had slipped more than 
1200 points to below 20000 rebounded to cut the days loss to 
76164 points 
the surge picked up momentum tuesday volume was estimated at 
550 million shares up from 428 million shares monday 
talk about herd mentality this market has gone 
completely and utterly bananas paul muller manager of 
international equity sales at schroder securities japan ltd 
said before tuesdays trading ended 
the rise was accelerated by panic buying according to yip 
customers were worried about missing the boat she said 
theyre afraid the markets going to pull back tomorrow 
theyre moving entirely differently from logic 
dealers said the runup was fed by a socalled short squeeze 
in which traders who had sold borrowed shares had to buy them back 
to avoid serious losses 
the short squeeze is on schroders muller said everyone 
had been expecting it and it came with a vengeance 
some traders believed the market had bottomed out and was ready 
for a change 
in addition to the psychological effect of hashimotos 
measure the market weary of selling was prepared for an 
upturn said yoshiro inoue a dealer with nomura securities 
diplomatic efforts by countries to settle the persian gulf 
crisis falling oil prices a surge in the dow jones industrial 
average on wall street monday and a stronger bond market in japan 
were also among the positive factors he said 
in bond dealings bond prices advanced as the yield on the 
benchmark 10year japanese government bond closed at 8185 percent 
down sharply from 8475 percent the previous day 
we believe todays rebound is an indication of sustained 
recovery as long as the middle east remains calm inoue said 
before the rebound the nikkei index had shed 1061613 points 
or 344 percent from its closing of 3083799 on aug 1 the day 
before iraq invaded kuwait 
japan is highly vulnerable to unrest in the gulf because it 
imports virtually all its oil with 70 percent coming from the 
middle east 
because the economy remains susceptible to outside shocks some 
doubted the lasting impact of the ministrys initiatives but many 
felt they would give the market a healthy shortterm boost 
the principal change would increase the credit limit for 
investors buying stock on margin the measure would allow investors 
to count 80 percent of the value of their holdings as collateral 
for stock purchases up from 70 percent 
a second measure aimed at easing market volatility reduces the 
time allowed for futures and options trading by 20 minutes to four 
hours and 10 minutes as in the united states traders in japan 
have been hedging their stock bets with counterbalancing trades in 
stockindex futures and options some critics say those strategies 
have contributed to the markets uneasiness 
the third measure loosens reporting requirements for big 
insurance companies investing in stocks which could spur more 
buying by those companies 
